  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, governments around the world, including the United States, have laws against money laundering. These laws are designed to prevent criminals from disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, making it appear legitimate.\n\nIn the United States, key legislation includes:\n\n*   **The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970:** Requires financial institutions to keep records of cash transactions exceeding a certain threshold and to report suspicious activity.\n*   **The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** Criminalized money laundering at the federal level.\n*   **The USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:** Expanded the scope of anti-money laundering laws in response to the September 11th attacks.",
